Question: What is an Entity-Relationship (ER) model?
Example answer: An Entity-Relationship model is a conceptual data model used to
  describe the structure of a database. It represents entities
  (objects or concepts), attributes (properties of entities), and
  relationships (associations between entities). ER diagrams visually
  depict these components and are used as a blueprint for designing
  relational database schemas.
Predicted answer: An Entity-Relationship (ER) model is a conceptual framework used to
  model data in databases, consisting of entities (represented as
  objects or concepts) and the relationships between them. ER models
  are visually depicted through ER diagrams and can be translated into
  relational models, making them useful for database design. They can
  exist in various levels of detail, including conceptual, logical,
  and physical models.
